I"U<p>This metaphor describes the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brains-are-like-forests">brain</a> as the combination of a monkey and a supercomputer. <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/cortical-subcortical-conflict-generates-limbic-friction">Subcortical structures are the monkey brain</a>, while the neocortex is the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/post-digital-computing-promises-superb-energy-efficiency">supercomputer</a>. The brain-monkey-supercomputer metaphor highlights different “attitudes” typically associated with cortical and subcortical <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/triune-brain-model-classifies-brain-regions-through-evolutionary-lens">structures</a>. Subcortical ones are stereotypically primitive and savage, while the cortical structures are allegedly sophisticated and elegant.</p>
